<font color="#FF0000">TO DOC</font><br>
<tt>Sun Aug 10 23:32:58 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc,<br><br>
I understand what you mean.  We are the sum of our experiences which includes the philosophies we cling to.  I know mine and am learning yours as well as others.  If I am ever to understand you I must know what beliefs you cling to.<br><br>
I have begun to post only because I felt the site or more importantly people I care about were losing perspective.  The damage to those who suffer from the war is tremendous.  This is site can be for many things, but it should not lose focus on the healing process.  Yours to I think.  We all have our demons.<br><br>
I felt your views or at least the way you presented them touched too many trigger points which included mine.  I would not expect that you and I could ever agree on the fighting man, but maybe close the gap.  I specifically focus on the man or woman not on war.  We ask a lot of our young men.  They are not war or politics.  We were all afraid, but we served and gave everything a man could give.  That deserves respect, but we have learned to not expect too much.<br><br>
I am one of those who spent more than two tours.  several years.  I watched the war in Nam close and switched to Cambodia.  I have too many battle stars and saw and heard too much.<br><br>
I merely suggest we spend more time discovering and learning to respect each others beliefs.  Ed has done an outstanding job.  I have studied the Native American beliefs for years and find them adding to my strength.  Ed has expanded them further.<br><br>
I have seen a turn toward honesty.  This can never meld two diverse positions, but it can lead to harmony.<br><br>
I will continue to watch the dialogue and if possible will contribute.  I wouldn't have offered this if you had not asked.
<p><code>--   (Silent Warrior) </code><p>


